This design represents a distributed web infrastructure for www.foobar.com with three servers.

### New Elements and Why They Are Added:
1. Load Balancer (HAproxy): Added to distribute incoming traffic across multiple servers, improving reliability and performance.
2. Additional Server: Added to eliminate a single point of failure at the application level and handle more concurrent users.

### Load Balancer Specifics:
- Algorithm: Round Robin. This algorithm works by sending each new request to the next server in a rotating list, ensuring an equal distribution of traffic.
- Setup: Active-Active. In this setup, both servers are processing requests simultaneously. In an Active-Passive setup, one server is active while the other remains idle, only taking over if the active one fails.

### Database Primary-Replica (Master-Slave) Cluster:
- Working Mechanism: The Primary (Master) node handles all data writes (INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE). These changes are then synchronized to the Replica (Slave) node.
- Application Difference: The application sends all 'write' operations to the Primary node and 'read' operations to the Replica node to reduce the load on the Primary.

### Infrastructure Issues:
- SPOF (Single Point of Failure): The Load Balancer itself is a SPOF. If HAproxy fails, the whole infrastructure becomes unreachable. The Database Primary node is also a SPOF for write operations.
- Security Issues: There is no Firewall to block unauthorized traffic, and no HTTPS to encrypt data between the user and the server.
- Monitoring: There is no system to track the health of the servers or alert the team if a service crashes.
